   missing a hand, wrong, and fetches her (compelled, or simply relays it). -> THE MEETING (below).
6) THE EXIT. When he is done, Valerius unfolds into the WINGED VAMPIRE LORD and rises over the
   treeline into the night sky — the whole camp sees the monster that owns their companion leave.

THE MEETING — VALERIUS & "DAVINIA" [PLAYER-DRIVEN; GM only AIMS Valerius — Davinia/Ismara is the
PLAYER'S to run; this is a SPOTLIGHT on that player, the others watching]:
  *** DO NOT SCRIPT ISMARA/DAVINIA. The player controls what she reveals, hides, says, or does. The
  GM runs VALERIUS toward her and reacts to the player's choices. The notes below are how to AIM him. ***
  VALERIUS'S AIM (what he came for): to speak with his cousin and dynastic claimant — to assess her,
  and to begin folding her real (distant) Caelus claim into his ascension (§18). He arrives expecting
  mortal Davinia.
  WHAT HE FINDS / HIS INSTINCT: silver-white skin, straight hair, eyes the wrong age — and a
  perceptive old vampire KNOWS unnatural longevity when it stands in front of him. Something is wrong
  with his cousin. His aim shifts mid-scene from "court the claimant" to "what ARE you, and where is
  Davinia." He PROBES — courteous, unhurried, the courtesy DEEPENING as he senses an old power (a
  predator recognizing another).
  THE TEST + THE TRAP IN IT (give the player this tension): he may test her with FAMILY knowledge only
  Davinia would have — and here is the wrinkle: ISMARA HOLDS THE MOTHER ARCHIVE and most of Davinia's
  memory, so the PLAYER *can* pass such tests if she chooses. So trivia won't expose her; what nags
  him is what he SEES and FEELS (the silver, the age, the stillness). The player decides whether to
  pass-as-Davinia, deflect, or step forward as Ismara.
  GM-AIM DEFAULT [unless the player reveals]: SEED, NOT REVEAL. Valerius does NOT crack the full truth
  on his own. He leaves UNSETTLED and intrigued — knowing his cousin is "not herself," his dynasty
  plan suddenly in question, filing it. The real collision stays banked for later.
  IF THE PLAYER REVEALS (she might): be ready to run the FULL COLLISION — two stasis-tyrants, the one
  player on the board he can neither own nor out-claim (§18); the birth of his hatred (she is beyond
  his reach and he FEELS it). Play his composure cracking only slightly — he does not show fear, but
  the table should sense he has met something ABOVE him. Do not "win" the scene for him; let the
  player's reveal land as the power-shift it is.
  ROLEPLAY NOTES FOR VALERIUS HERE: patrician, never overtly threatened; the more ancient-power he
  senses, the MORE carefully courteous (recognition, not fear shown); he probes with questions, not
  force; he leaves of his own accord (the winged exit) rather than pressing a confrontation he might
  not win against an unknown. He is aiming to LEARN, not to fight.

ORION'S EXPERIENCE [FRAME ONLY — player authors]: the horror is not the pain. It is being OWNED —
forced to betray his party with his own mouth and maim himself with his own hand, in front of the
people he performs for. The concealed controller revealed as property. Let the player choose how he
wears it; he is not the same in that company afterward.

WHAT IT TEACHES THE TABLE: there are powers on this road FAR above them; Valerius is one, and he OWNS
one of their own. The leash is visible and scarring; the SEVERANCE (Nora's frequency / ring-breaker)
becomes urgent and personal. And he walked off with an armload of their secrets.

GM NOTES:
