§24 — MAVEN & THE BLACK-BRIARS (planning, from the lore cross-ref) [PROPOSED]
=====================================================================
Source: the fudgemuppet Black-Briar lore video, cross-referenced against our canon.
RULE: our established canon (Maven debrief scene, Hemming scene, Honorhall pipeline,
present-reality tracker, web) is the REAL TRUTH and supersedes the game/video wherever
they conflict. Below = what we KEEP, what we CORRECT, and the design decisions we made
talking it through.

--- WHO MAVEN ACTUALLY IS (the corrected read — this is the spine) ---
Maven is NOT a tyrant of stasis (that's Valerius). She is an AGENT OF CHANGE she must
MONOPOLIZE. She tore out Riften's old fishing/honey economy and rebuilt the city around
her meadery; she constantly reshapes the guards, the Jarl's circle, the Guild's loyalties,
the flow of every deal. She is the AUTHOR of the status quo, over and over. The one
inviolable rule: nothing in Riften changes unless SHE steers it and profits from it.
  - This REFRAMES the Grelod kill. The party's true violation was NOT moral (she doesn't
    care Grelod ran a child-pipeline) and NOT yet operational — it was making a CHANGE in
    her city that she did not author. That is the unforgivable thing, in her terms.
  - Distinct from Valerius on purpose: he wants nothing to ever change again; she wants to
    be the only one allowed to change anything. Two different tyrannies, not one flavor.

CAMPAIGN VILLAIN SIGNATURE (worth holding for future antagonists): our serious
antagonists are moved by CONTROL OF INFORMATION AND OUTCOMES, not cruelty for its own
sake. Maven's compass isn't "is this wrong," it's "is this NOISE / did I authorize it."
Valerius states consequences as facts; Ismara never lies, only curates; Maven only asks
who authored the change. Competence-tyranny, not mustache-twirling.

THE ONE CRACK (humanization, bank for later): the blanket in the chair — she slept beside
dying Hemming for a week. Not redemption; proof she can love and channels every drop of it
into control and protection, never warmth. Pair with Riften's economic history (she saved
a near-burnt-down city ~50 yrs ago by opening the meadery) — treated as TRUE HISTORY that
explains why she's so powerful.

HEMMING = the child who REFUSED to become her. His letter runs on TRUST; hers on FEAR.
Pattern across the campaign: children of power either BECOME it or become its OPPOSITE,
no third option (cf. Nora vs. what Ismara might make of her; Alfonso's Vrykolas synthesis).

--- SEQUENCING LOCKS ---
- SIBBI & INGUN: do NOT introduce before the FALL OF RIFTEN. Introducing them now only to
  have Riften's destined destruction wipe them out wastes the material (risks killing the
  whole Black-Briar family in one stroke). [LOCKED]
- INGUN (post-Riften wire, not now): the alchemist who wants "darker circles," fascinated
  by watching the body fail — reads like she's trying to be the FAMILY'S third-option child
  nobody's managed. Puts her in genuine proximity to Namira/Peryite's orbit later. A live
  wire to develop AFTER the fall, alongside whoever of the family survives.

--- DIRGE / THE GRELOD RECKONING (corrected — REFRAMED: assembly, not discovery) ---
- THE BIG CORRECTION: the fuse is NOT "she has to find evidence." She and her Guild
  ALREADY HOLD EVERY PIECE. Discovery = her ATTENTION turning hostile enough to bother
  assembling what she has. (Full breakdown in present reality → "THE MAVEN FUSE" and
  ch.24 outline → GRELOD JOB.) The pieces, all grounded in the record:
    • GRELOD'S DEATH IS A PLAIN STAB-MURDER — rapier through the heart. NOT a plague
      death (the infected are still incubating, ASYMPTOMATIC; the outbreak surfaces
      later). So the scene reads as a clean assassination from the start.
    • THE HAYLOFT GIRL (Ch.22): she saw Orion + Alfonso kill the homeless woman the
      SAME WAY (rapier-stab MO) AND saw Orion FEED (vampire tell). Maven SILENCED her —
      which transferred that testimony into MAVEN'S PRIVATE FILES. So Maven already holds:
      the Lanterns stab-kill and cover up in her city, matching Grelod's MO; and Orion
      feeds like a vampire.
    • THE BOOK-COLLATERAL (the Ratway beat): the Guild (= Maven's) knows Orion is a
      vampire (a SECOND, independent source), knows he used a "train under Grelod"
      pretext to get close, and knows he reclaimed his collateral the day before she died.
- CONSEQUENCE: nothing left to DISCOVER. When her attention turns — most naturally when
  the PARTY hands her a fresh reason — she assembles it and sends DIRGE (her Guild
  enforcer, the ratways chokepoint sentry) to kill the responsible Lantern(s). Not a
  random target, not Constance. GM's prep job is now just the SPARK (what turns her
  attention) + Dirge's capability. Whether/how the party retaliates is THEIRS to drive.
- IT'S PRIVATE, NOT PUBLIC: everything she holds is ammunition in her hand, never a
  public case. She ruins them her way (leverage), or kills quietly (Dirge) — not a trial.

--- THE BLACKMAIL COUNTER-PLAY (Orion's fight) ---
- Runs through ORION specifically, because Maven ALREADY holds his vampirism over him —
  so the info-war is MUTUAL: he's both best-equipped to run it (Guile; nearly beat her in
